<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1891-08-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1891-08-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="19" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d19">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wharton</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Grant</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1891-08-06"><hi rend="italic">August 6,
                            1891</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 133.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In reply to your dispatch No. 168, of the 15th
                        ultimo, in relation to the case of Nikolaus Bader, the assisted emigrant,
                        you may address a dignified note to the foreign office in the sense you
                        suggest, saying, <pb facs="0127" n="21" xml:id="pg_21"/> in conclusion,
                        that, as Bader has been returned, pursuant to the statutes of the United
                        States, to the country whence he was assisted to emigrate, the incident may
                        be regarded as terminated.</p>
                    <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">William F. Wharton</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary</hi>.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>